0":"1120–1200","1150–1204":"1150–1204","environ 1201":"about 1201","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1236":"1236","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","1120":"1120","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","Meyrargues, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Meyrargues, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France","Mévouillon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Mévouillon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","Les Baux-de-Provence, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Les Baux-de-Provence, Bouches-du-Rhône, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sabran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eliyahu, Hersh, Hyman, Mayer, Nadav, Zev.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Hungarian (<b>Sáfrán</b>); Croatian and Slovenian (<b>Šafran</b>); Czech and Slovak (<b>Šafran</b> and <b>Šafrán</b>): from Middle High German <i>saffrān</i>, German <i>Safran</i>, Hungarian <i>sáfrány</i>, Slavic <i>šafran</i> (standard Slovenian is <i>žafran</i>; see below) ‘saffron’, a bright yellow spice and colorant derived from the stigmas of a crocus, hence a metonymic occupational name for a spicer or a nickname for someone with reddish-yellow hair. The word is ultimately derived from Arabic <i>zaʿfarān</i>. The Jewish name is mainly artificial.","Americanized form of Polish   Szafran   and Slovenian <b>Žafran</b>: from Polish <i>szafran</i>, Slovenian <i>žafran</i> ‘saffron’, words of the same ultimately Arabic origin as above."],"variants":[{"name":"Shafran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Simcha, Avi, Meyer, Shoshana, Tsilya, Uri.  Russian Anatoly, Mikhail, Natalya, Oleg, Semyon, Yuriy.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): mainly artificial name, cognate with   Safran  , from eastern Yiddish <i>shafran</i>, Polish <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’."]},{"name":"Szafranski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Bogdan, Halina, Krzysztof, Miroslaw, Stanislaw, Tadeuz, Wieslaw.","Polish (<b>Szafrański</b>): habitational name for someone from either of two places called Szafranki in Masovian and Podlaskie voivodeships, or Szafranów, in Masovian and Podkarpackie voivodeships, all named with <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’ (see   Safran   1). Compare   Safranski  ."]},{"name":"Szafran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Karol.","Polish, Rusyn (from Poland), and Jewish (from Poland): from Polish <i>szafran</i> ‘saffron’, a topographic name for someone who lived where the saffron crocus grew, a metonymic occupational name for a spicer, or possibly a nickname for someone with yellow hair. See also   Safran  ."]},{"name":"Saffran","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Safran  ."]},{"name":"Safranek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Šafránek</b>): from a diminutive of Czech <i>šafrán</i> ‘saffron’ (see   Safran  ), applied as nickname for someone with reddish yellow hair."]}]},{"name":"Ermengarz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."],"variants":[{"name":"Irmengard","meanings":["Variant of   Ermengard ."]},{"name":"Irmingard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Ermgard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Irmgard","meanings":["Variant of   Ermengard ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ermengarz de Mévouillon de Sabran was born in 1172, in Mévouillon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, her father, Guillaume de Sabran, was 53 and her mother, Sinispella de Lacon serra, was 22. She married Bertrand II des Baux-d'Orange. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1225, in Meyrargues, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1172–1225":"1172–1225","1163–1201":"1163–1201","1188–1236":"1188–1236","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1150–1204":"1150–1204","environ 1201":"umbes 1201","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1236":"1236","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","1120":"1120","1163":"1163","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","Meyrargues, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Meyrargues, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Prantsusmaa","Mévouillon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Mévouillon, Drôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Les Baux-de-Provence, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Les Baux-de-Provence, Bouches-du-Rhône, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1172–1225":